WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:08.988
The last experiment they do is these linear probes, which where they just go and they just build classifiers from different parts of the network.

00:09.690 --> 00:14.880
And you can see right here that what is predicted and how well they work.

00:14.900 --> 00:18.968
So each bar here is going to be the difference of performance.

00:18.988 --> 00:22.815
So this is differential performance of diagnostic classifier by layer.

00:22.795 --> 00:25.602
sorted by task order in figure eight.

00:26.284 --> 00:31.316
Each plot shows the change in performance between the given layer and the previous layer.

00:33.101 --> 00:40.399
So a bar up shows it's performing better than the previous layer, a bar down shows it's performing worse than the previous layer.

00:40.379 --> 00:45.750
You see right here that these are the secondary structures right here.

00:46.371 --> 00:55.309
You can see that there is a lot of performance in the earlier layers right here and not that high performance in the later layers.

00:55.730 --> 00:59.518
Whereas for the tertiary structures, the binding site and the contact,

00:59.498 --> 01:19.380
You can see that there is a bit of performance in places, but it sort of tends to be more towards the middle, certainly more towards the middle of the end of the network than the secondary structures, which sort of makes sense with our hypothesis.

01:19.360 --> 01:40.035
You can also see this here, where they show the percent of attention focused as a function of layer, and the red is the center of mass, and you can see that as the secondary structure, their center of mass is at a lower layer in general than the tertiary.

